text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text_retweet:
#blackhistorymonth
#repost from @equalityequation 
#taranaburke's career has been spent uniting us; #metoo allowed 19 million people across 85 countries to declare that we've been affected by sexual violence. @girlsforgenderequity, the non-profit she founded, creates opportunities for young women and girls to live self-determined lives by tackling the many obstacles young women and girls face such as sexism, racial inequality, homophobia, transphobia, and sexual harassment. her most recent work with the #muterkelly movement has allowed the rest of the world to connect to the scores of black women who have, until now, had to stand in silence as the violence, manipulation and abuse they suffered went ignored, and r kelly's wealth built. her involvement in the project has opened us to the prevalence of sexual violence, to its insidiousness, and to our ability to heal each other when we choose to #believewomen. 
for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

#taranaburke's career has been spent uniting us; #metoo allowed 19 million people across 85 countries to declare that we've been affected by sexual violence. @girlsforgenderequity, the non-profit she founded, creates opportunities for young women and girls to live self-determined lives by tackling the many obstacles young women and girls face such as sexism, racial inequality, homophobia, transphobia, and sexual harassment. her most recent work with the #muterkelly movement has allowed the rest of the world to connect to the scores of black women who have, until now, had to stand in silence as the violence, manipulation and abuse they suffered went ignored, and r kelly's wealth built. her involvement in the project has opened us to the prevalence of sexual violence, to its insidiousness, and to our ability to heal each other when we choose to #believewomen. 
for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

text:
#taranaburke's career has been spent uniting us; #metoo allowed 19 million people across 85 countries to declare that we've been affected by sexual violence. just be, the non-profit she founded, focusing on the health, well-being, and wholeness of young women of color, sought to empower and provide guidance to girls as they begin to define themselves. her most recent work with the #muterkelly movement has allowed the rest of the world to connect to the scores of black women who have, until now, had to stand in silence as the violence, manipulation and abuse they suffered went ignored, and r kelly's wealth built. her involvement in the project has opened us to the prevalence of sexual violence, to its insidiousness, and to our ability to heal each other when we choose to #believewomen. 
for teaching us how to listen and for her work ending the suffering in silence, this #blackhistorymonth we honor @taranajaneen
.

text:
ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ know your rights is here!! ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ (link in profile)
.

a midwife seemed like a good fit for me until she told me i needed to schedule an induction once i went past 41 weeks.  i never got a good reason why.
.
so, at 41 weeks and 6 days pregnant, with the help of my doula, i switched to a different hospital and midwife, who was willing to lay out all my options and support me in my *free* choice about what i wanted to do.  i was really lucky to find a care provider who was willing to take me that late in pregnancy.  i ended up having my baby the very next day with no complications in a respectful environment with no unnecessary medical intervention.
.
but i didnâ€™t really know my rights.  i didnâ€™t really think i *needed* to know my rights--until i got in hot water.
.
everything worked out just fine, but the whole thing left me with a lot of questions about my own rights in that situation. what might have happened if another care provider hadnâ€™t turned up for me?  what rights did i have to stand on, what rights belonged to me, to protect myself and my baby? .
the more i researched and spoke with other people who had given birth, the more surprised i was to realize what strong rights i had had to say no, and how commonly that right is violated in maternity care.
.
that was seven years ago!  today, i'm releasing know your rights: legal and human rights in childbirth for birth professionals & advocates (link in profile)--a product of years working with top lawyers and advocates trying to untangle this dilemma.  it's a must for anyone working in birth.  period.
.

so, at 41 weeks and 6 days pregt, with the help of my doula, i switched to a different hospital and midwife, who was willing to lay out all my options and support me in my *free* choice about what i wanted to do.  i was really lucky to find a care provider who was willing to take me that late in pregcy.  i ended up having my baby the very next day with no complications in a respectful environment with no unnecessary medical intervention.
.
but i didnâ€™t really know my rights.  i didnâ€™t really think i *needed* to know my rights--until i got in hot water.
.
everything worked out just fine, but the whole thing left me with a lot of questions about my own rights in that situation. what might have happened if another care provider hadnâ€™t turned up for me?  what rights did i have to stand on, what rights belonged to me, to protect myself and my baby? .
the more i researched and spoke with other people who had given birth, the more surprised i was to realize what strong rights i had had to say no, and how commonly that right is violated in maternity care.
.
that was seven years ago!  today, i am releasing know your rights: legal and human rights in childbirth for birth professionals & advocates (link in profile)--a product of years working with top lawyers and advocates trying to untangle this dilemma.  it is a must for anyone working in birth.  period.
.

text:
i'm fine...
_
two words that mask a lot...
_
along with ok...
_
ok... is exactly how i've been lately.
_
how you doing chels?
_
i'm ok...
_
until i broke down yesterday.
_
i had enough.
_
i was fed up being ok...
_
and had to actually say... no i'm not.
_
i cried a lot.. and then guess what? 
_
i really was ok...
_
it's important to allow yourself to check in with what's going on.
_
i'm very good at coping and processing... and have a great awareness about what's going on but what i didn't realise is that for a moment...
_
i forgot to feel.
_
so it was building ... underneath the surface...
_
until it hit me.
_
and guess what, today i woke up... _
stronger, focused and more determined then i have been for awhile.
_
don't forget to feel...
_
you can only move forward when you are whole...
_
the good and the bad.
the love and the hurt.
_
it is all you... and you've got this!
_
(drawing by me, words left by others) â¤ï¸

i had enough.

stronger, focused and more determined then i have been for awhile.
_
do not forget to feel...
_
you can only move forward when you are whole...

the good and the bad.
the love and the hurt.
_
it is all you... and you have got this!

but iâ€™m not forgiving my abuser. heâ€™s taken so much from me: my physical health, my mental health, relationships with others, so much money, and even more time. and to hurt me is one thing, but i know other women who have come forward about the same man. he doesnâ€™t deserve my forgiveness.

and iâ€™m okay with that. iâ€™ve been able to heal despite the fact that i havenâ€™t forgiven him. my life feels complete now and i donâ€™t need the peace that comes with forgiving him in order to move on with my life. we all heal differently and if you feel like you canâ€™t ever forgive the person who hurt you, then donâ€™t. you have that right. ğŸ’œğŸ’™ #weareher

as long as i could remember i have loved taking picture.  now donâ€™t get me wrong.  i am not a professional and i donâ€™t want to be.  i just like documenting all the things i am doing.  looking back at old photo albums the other day and even some scrapbooks i made in the past was so fun.  every picture tells a story and each story is a memory.  this picture was from our trip to colorado last fall. so beautiful and the memories from that trip are priceless. as a memory care director we use old photos to help trigger a memory, sometimes it works and other times it doesnâ€™t but it was fun to see what they say in regards to the pictures. .

text:
according to the national sexual violence resource center * 1 in 5 women and 1 in 71 men will be raped at some point in their lives.
* in the united stares 1 in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance.
* 52.4% of male victims report being raped by an acquaintance and 15.1% by a stranger.
* 49.5% of multiracial women and over 45% of american indian/alaska native women were subjected to some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime.
* 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and 9% are male * in 8 out of 10 cases of rape, the victim knew the perpetrator.
* 8% of rapes occur while the victim is at work. 
the problem of sexual violence runs rampant, and yet rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. of the remaining 37% that are reported less than 10% are instances of false reporting. the facts are clear, and still the culture that would rather victims of sexually based crimes remain silent prevails. 
join rebecca macceile as she throws off the shackles of silence and raises her voice. turquoise boot straps: a survivorâ€™s thoughts provides a glimpse into her journey of self discovery while tackling many controversial topics at the height of the metoo era. #comingsoon #saam #nsvrc #indieauthor #newrelease #pstdsurvivor #metoo available at the #linkinbio april 2019 #newreads #bookstagram

feb 13 my new beginning / new year! ğŸ€unlucky 13? â˜˜ nahhhhh 
six years ago i walked into an empty house.  my ex left me for another woman.  this day.... just before valentine's day will forever be like new years eve to me, a reminder not of an ending but a new beginning. 
it reminds me not of how little i was loved but how lucky i have been to have survived both physically in the literal sense and emotionally as well. that man would have killed me or we killed each other.  he used to say "one of these days you're gonna shoot me." he was right.  i was tired of being knocked unconscious or choked out.  i feared one day would be the last day or he would hurt me terribly.  i feared for my life.

i am still working hard to figure it out and still fucking up tremendously... but i am moving forward and the life lessons are worth it.  i am figuring this out little by little.  no more flinching around men.  boundaries strong.  happy, healthy, loved and adored.  my life is blessed.

text:
not everyone deserves the benefit of the doubt. not everyone deserves an opportunity to show they've changed. not everyone deserves a chance. sometimes its best to listen to the horror stories people warn you.

two years ago. i remember two years ago. i had just joined the @sdaffl football league the week prior. i remember i was running the convention center stairs with my football coach & another friend from the football league when i got a text from my then best friend of almost 10yrs. he was super emotional. i headed over after the stairs.

i remember showing up and he was upset punching the walls, angry, screaming, crying over his recent breakup. i started trying to talk him down which had become the norm. after awhile he asked if i wanted a drink. he made me a drink. i remember this straight man trying to make out with me & me pushing him away & saying no over & over again. then i froze. you hear a lot about fight or flight. i froze. 
i remember every second, every moment of my rape, but i remember it as if i wasn't there. i seperated from my body. i remember him saying over and over "you're such a good boy" and "this is a first for me. i've never done this before." i remember showering after in a state of shock not fully realizing what happened. it took me several months to even mention or accept what happened that night. it took a near suicide attempt & being scared to leave my house to accept what happened that night. i remember going to church, showing up to practices, going to the games, going bacl to the gym and hearing people ask what's wrong with you, why are you freaking out, are you ok? two years. two years ago. i remember everything... not everyone deserves the benefit of the doubt.

i'm a better person now. i still freak out sometimes & need my alone time. i still have anxiety. i still have trust issues in relationships. i still have guards up against any intimacy. i'm still not ok, but i'm so much more ok than i've ever been. i know something good will come out of this. so much already has

â€œsince trump took office, the women of congress have become use to making public messages. they wore white to his inauguration and wore black to the #sotu in 2018 to show support for the #timesup and #metoo movements. this year, they all wore suffragette white yet again in solidarity with women all over. this coupled with their collective clapping and cheering when the accomplishments of women were mentioned, garnered quick criticism.
âš¢ğŸ”¥
a meme began surfacing claiming that these women were told what to wear and when to clap. it paid no regard to the meaning behind their fashion nor what they were all clapping for. it condemned them for making their own choices and celebrating their accomplishments as women. âš¢ğŸ”¥
society would much rather tell a woman how to act and condemn her when she falls astray than let her make her own choices. this double standard has to stop. i can guarantee you that if it were then men in congress all coordinating some sort of message they would be praised for it. for their heroism and speaking out. but a woman? no way.
âš¢ğŸ”¥
the message the women of congress shared should be celebrated. this action showed the intersectionality of our fight as feminists. the camaraderie and sisterhood displayed at this yearâ€™s #sotu is inspiring. we have more strong women in congress that represent diversity and that is something that should be talked about. âš¢ğŸ”¥
itâ€™s 2019 and women arenâ€™t here for your petty double standardsâ€ #linkinbio

text:
sabrina by nick drnaso
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
what do you do when a loved one goes missing? sabrina leaves her home one day in chicago and that is the last time anyone (nice) sees her. soon after, a video surfaces on the internet that clarifies her whereabouts and leaves her family and boyfriend grappling with the ultimate grief.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
with quiet, subtle precision, drnaso sheds a light on the obsessive conspiracy theory culture that makes up some of the dark corners of the internet (coincidentally, also the same space where alt-right whack jobs that host radio shows can be found). he correctly points to the sad reality of our times where motivation to churn out, and profit from, negative content seems to be at an all-time high.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
the only graphic novel to have been considered by the man booker prize (longlisted in 2018), sabrina is an important, albeit heartbreaking, read especially in the era of online trolling, â€œalternative factsâ€ and maga hats. rating: 5/5.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text: i was late opening bibi moon @bibimoonboutique yesterday because i was having a ridiculously fun, absolutely silly, and completely thought provoking conversation with a room filled with 6 amazing women, and 2 brave sweet boys... @jimjefferies @theovon âœ¨the common denominator was my incredibly amazing customer and friend lauren @lro_senberg ğŸ‘‘she asked me to come to this meeting to discuss feminist issues with a couple of men who were friends of a comedienne whitney @whitneycummings and wanted feedback from strong opinionated women about their upcoming acts in the age of #metoo etc...as part of the pilot for her show man up on @comedycentral . while i am actually uncomfortable with being called a feminist because that word is so heavily charged with connotations & associations that i don't feel further the empowerment and equanimity of women, but in fact can alienate both sexes and ultimately end conversations and block dialogues that seek to illuminate and unite-i am a lifelong female who bears scars from decades on the battlefield of fighting to live my life in an way that has been criticized, negated, berated, belittled because i have followed paths, that if i had been a man would have been called adventurous and brave, but instead were deemed irresponsible, selfish, and just plain crazy. âœ¨âœ¨ln the end, i didn't contribute much to the conversation, i was happy just to be a fly on the wall basically listening and laughing non stop to the group. âœ¨yet, i walked away with this tremendous sense of compassion for these two men (who revealed themselves to be incredible sensitive, vulnerable and confused in this world of women and surprisingly shared very personal details of their lives + upbringing) as well as a renewed understanding that men are all little boys (lots of potty & penis talk...)who are perhaps desperately seeking sex, but ultimately approval, attention, affirmation, adoration, and above all, love....which as women,gives us enormous power-and the more we acknowledge and own our feminine power, if we play our "cards" right, we will find greater and more equal footing in this world, and harmony. âœ¨after all, love is the highest common denominator of us all.

now that iâ€™m a few weeks down the line  iâ€™m bloody glad it all fell through. this research isnâ€™t going to waste away in some library. this research isnâ€™t going to become confined to just statistics that ignore real life. this research is going to be about real men with real stories in the real world.

2. my brother has depression, anxiety and when younger, social phobia. this experience really shaped who i am today.

4. #metoo

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

i don't know how many of you are truly prepared to know the amount of people that you know that have been sexually assaulted. the #metoomovement put it into perspective for a lot of people, but do you really know how common place sexual assault is?

here's my experience:
a month before my sixteenth birthday, i was sexually assaulted to a very extreme extent, by someone i had known my entire life. my abuser has since passed away. i was vocal about it, until my entire family called me a liar. then, i shut up; i didn't like rocking the boat as a kid, and as a teenager, the rebellion streak hit me very, very late. i kept quiet again until i met my ex-fiancÃ©, whom i confided everything in. instead of truly believing me, he set about psychologically conditioning me instead. he had become close with my abuser, and after asking him about my allegations, he learned things, never sharing them, instead using them to abuse me himself. i became his subservient, not through my own will, but through the manipulation of my dependency issues, my fragile and decaying mental health, and past traumas. i would do whatever he asked if me, as he was all i had, and if you asked me in 2009, all i needed. he eventually left me in 2012, when his brainwashing started to wane; i matured very quickly while with him, and he pushed me enough to break free of the limits he had imposed on me. whether this was his intention remains a mystery i don't care to solve. i'm a different person now in every sense of the word, though, because of what happened on 2/13/06. i am not broken or weaker because of the things i've been through, i'm stronger, and smarter. i have been irreparably damaged by the things i was subjected to by these two men in particular, but i have had a bakers dozen of encounters of men groping, harassing, stalking, and assaulting me since then.
the last guy got socked.
im making progress with every guy i check.

it's been 13 years. and this is the first full public statement. but not the last.

thank you, @courtwithconfidence
for giving me the confidence to share my story!

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text: this is the first time in 30 years that the state legislature is holding a hearing on sexual harassment. the #metoo moment has revealed what many of us have known for far too long - that sexual harassment is pervasive across all sectors of the economy and that we as a society and as a legislative body have a tremendous amount of work to do to make all workplaces safe for all workers. today's hearing is long overdue, and should signal the beginning but not the end of an ongoing conversation about the steps that we must take today and every day to ensure that women in the workforce can reach and exceed their full potential.

text:
a safety plan is a living document that outlines how your family plans to keep your children safe from sexual abuse. it is not merely a list of "rules", but it is a lifestyle that incorporates behaviors that family members and non-family are required to adhere to if they are going to continue to have access to your child. your safety plan will change as your child grows and matures to incorporate safety behaviors that align with their activities outside of the home as well as social responsibilities regarding the opposite sex. an example of a few of these behaviors might include....
1) children are not forced to show affection to anyone.
2) children don't sit in the laps of family or friends.
3) children are always clothed during playtime with adults or other children.
4) if a child asks you not to touch them, their request is respected. 
5) children are taught that they should not be asked to keep secrets by any adult. explain the difference between secrets and surprises.
6) children should not be behind closed doors with teachers, coaches, or church leaders.
7) consent is required before touching another child. this includes kissing and hugging.
these are just a few that we suggest. what other behaviors would you incorporate into your family's safety plan? #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #super bowl

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

the guardian

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i made a post that asked the question, â€œhow do you navigate flirtation in the #metoo era?â€ and this question was directed to men. the reason i posted this is to open the conversation to see how men might be learning or struggling with this topic. and itâ€™s true, some men are scared of flirting because they donâ€™t want to be accused, and it needs to be talked about amongst men. i realize that i also have women who are part of my audience and that asking this kind of question has impact, and on a social media platform like facebook/instagram, it makes it an open forum. i welcome the opinions and iâ€™m grateful for the voices. .
.
.
this blog is a response, calling on men to be responsible for developing their emotional intelligence as a response to the #metoo movement, to doing the work of calling each other in, and supporting each other to heal toxic masculinity. it is uncomfortable work, but it must be done.
.
.
.

text:
i set off on a mission to not only see parts of the world that i wanted to see but to also write a book detailing my life story.Â  i believe that i had done the impossible and that is not hubris. i believe that i have been able to tap into a place of human potential that most cannot and the reason that i decided to write a book laying out my past and how i got to be the person i am today is because i know that if i can do it then anyone can.

now to the point. my blog will no longer be a â€œdigital nomadâ€ blog because honestly, i donâ€™t give a shit about being a digital nomad. i wanted to share my experiences in the world and i feel like i did that to the best of my ability. i am going to let this blog simply be what it is and that is whatever i feel like writing or sharing.Â  maybe writing a book and traveling the world qualifies as being a nomad but honestly, iâ€™m more interested in sharing my truth in a different way. i subtitled this blog traveling through trauma because i anticipated coming out the other side a different person. iâ€™m only getting started and nothing is the same.

thatâ€™s it. thatâ€™s all i got right now. itâ€™s midnight in vietnam and iâ€™m going to eat peanut butter and listen to tool because that shit makes me happy. -m

if you want to read the rest the link is in my bio.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

be happy and stay healthy, my dear!

text: tried to catch a rainbow today ğŸ˜‚. didnâ€™t work but i still love trying. maybe thatâ€™s a metaphor for love somehow lol. to all my sisters and brothers whoâ€™ve gone through caca and survived, rock on loves. i wish you the best as you move forward in this crazy thing called life. i met a woman this weekend whoâ€™s having a really hard time getting past her trauma. i sincerely empathized with her state of mind and being. being caught up in it is so hard... and at first glance you wouldnâ€™t know she was so traumatized. she looked like a typical oc housewife type. but within minutes of meeting her she admitted her truth and iâ€™m just a caring stranger... it was sign of how much the pain of it all is on her mind. itâ€™s right there for her with every breath, poor lady. so letâ€™s try this. letâ€™s challenge each other to a no judgment week! letâ€™s be open minded to people we come across daily and try to swipe the judgement to the side. donâ€™t judge the clothes or makeup or lack of either. just chat. see if you can see where someone else is coming from. i challenge you!!!!! let me know if anything exciting happens ğŸ˜‚. âŒâ­•ï¸âŒâ­•ï¸vuâ¤ï¸ğŸ’œ #vaginasunitedvu #ourdaughtersarewatching #yourvoicematters #metootimesup #metoo #metooisvu #timesup #believesurvivors #metoomovement #endrape #rapeculture #rapecultureiswhen #rapecultureisreal #womensmarch #believewomen #keepfighting #truth #metoostories #abuseawareness #endrapeoncampus #enoughisenough #whyididntreport #yourvoicematters #familyviolence #itsnothyourfault #womenunited #womenpower #womenempowerment #nomeansno #survivor

text:
assalamualaikum semua..
untuk tournament pes19 maaf yea korang.. dah full slot.. untuk mobile legend korang boleh baca di bawah tuu..
welcome to mobile legends

terima kasih kerana berminat menyertai pertandingan kami yang bertempat di kluang mall rooftop, kluang mall, kluang johor . pada 16 feb 2019. dari 10am hingga tamat. 
diingatkan kepada yang ingin turut serta , sila baca dan patuh syarat serta arahan terlebih dahulu sebelum anda mendaftar dan melakukan penbayaran bagi mengelakkan salah faham di hari kelak .

jika anda mempunyai squad yang bagus , ingin menjadi seperti air asia saiyan , icon , evos , saiyan reborn dan sebagainya . ayuh !!! serlahkan kehebatan , skills dan strategi pasukan anda . disinilah bermulanya pemain professional . ayuh ! tunggu apa lagi . *ikuti caraÂ² utk mendaftar*

1.sila bank in yuran penyertaan terlebih dahulu di akaun : *upper class men resources no.akaun: 551137526613 (maybank)*. sila rujuk pada penganjur terlebih dahulu untuk membuat bayaran .

2.kemudian maklumkan kepada penganjur bahawa pembayaran telah dibuat , *ambil gambar & simpan resit original anda* .

3.sila *double confirm* betulÂ² maklumat pasukan dan ahli anda sebelum mengisi borang tersebut . kesalahan dan kecuaian anda sendiri boleh mengakibat pasukan anda maklumat tidak diterima & tidak dibenarkan bertanding sama sekali .

4.sila submit borang & bayaran anda *serentak pada waktu yang sama* . slot adalah terhad , sebarang rayuan dan bantahan tidak akan dilayam sama sekali .

5.sila berikan butiran seperti berikut
1- nama pasukan
2- nama pemain (no ic) (no id ml)
3- pasukan mestilah memberikan 6 nama pemain (1 simpanan)
4- setiap pasukan dikenakan yuran pendaftaran sebanyak rm60 shj.

jom daftar sekarang
slot adalah terhad

untuk mendaftar pasukan anda sila hantar maklumat pasukan ke no whatapp 0177878388
segala masalah sila pm en rossi utk keterangan lanjut.
name: KETEGAQQ STUDIO

jika anda mempunyai squad yang bagus , ingin menjadi seperti air asia saiyan , icon , evos , saiyan reborn dan sebagainya . ayuh !!! serlahkan kehebatan , skills dan strategi pasukan anda . disinilah bermulanya pemain professional . ayuh ! tunggu apa lagi . *ikuti caraÂ² utk mendaftar*

1.sila bank in yuran penyertaan terlebih dahulu di akaun : *upper class men resources no.akaun: 551137526613 (maybank)*. sila rujuk pada penganjur terlebih dahulu untuk membuat bayaran .

2.kemudian maklumkan kepada penganjur bahawa pembayaran telah dibuat , *ambil gambar & simpan resit original anda* .

3.sila *double confirm* betulÂ² maklumat pasukan dan ahli anda sebelum mengisi borang tersebut . kesalahan dan kecuaian anda sendiri boleh mengakibat pasukan anda maklumat tidak diterima & tidak dibenarkan bertanding sama sekali .

4.sila submit borang & bayaran anda *serentak pada waktu yang sama* . slot adalah terhad , sebarang rayuan dan bantahan tidak akan dilayam sama sekali .

5.sila berikan butiran seperti berikut
1- nama pasukan
2- nama pemain (no ic) (no id ml)
3- pasukan mestilah memberikan 6 nama pemain (1 simpa)
4- setiap pasukan dikenakan yuran pendaftaran sebanyak rm60 shj.

jom daftar sekarang
slot adalah terhad

untuk mendaftar pasukan anda sila hantar maklumat pasukan ke no whatapp 0177878388
segala masalah sila pm en rossi utk keterangan lanjut.

text:
i donâ€™t know where to begin, other than to begin slightly overwhelmed and say i am 1000% honored to have sat nude for the highly talented painter @danielmaidman as he painted my portrait.  a few years back, in 2013, when i was living in chicago, i painted a piece titled â€œpower pussyâ€ that generated quite a bit of controversy.  daniel has known me since then and weâ€™ve maintained a great friendship. i believe i may have been joking with daniel at one point about him creating a second version of "power pussy," loosely based on the original powerful statement pose, and it quickly (in painting time anyway, over the course of a year and a half), became a reality.  thank you daniel, for giving me my head in this portrait, since in the original i left it off as a commentary about the hyper sexualization of women in our culture. this portrait feels powerful, yet soft. it feels bold, yet romantic.  it feels contemporary, yet timeless.  daniel captured my soul in this piece and itâ€™s at once frightening, and not, as it feels as if iâ€™m just staring into a mirror.  during the process of him painting i decided itâ€™d be a great idea to dig in with an interview, and ask questions about his process, life and how he feels being a painter in the modern era.  you donâ€™t want to miss his perfectly stated answers (he is after all a highly skilled writer as well), so please click the link in my bio and give the full video a watch. the finished painting can be seen right at the end.  thanks as always for watching. .

text:
tomorrow! join us for a valentineâ€™s day seminar hosted by @pncacriticalstudies 
jasmine johnson
thursday feb 14 from 11:00-12:30, hammer conference room

me too; now what? 
we've heard their stories, we've told our own but when and how does the healing begin?  jasmine, licensed clinical therapist,  provides an introduction to the journey to addressing and healing from all forms of sexual violence and violations.  this will jumpstart participants understanding and motivation to begin to work through the traumas associated with sexual harassment, rape, molestation, violence, and sexually inappropriate behaviors.  while the movement against those that violate has been a huge collective step, many are left with an open wound that affects them daily.  this seminar is designed to address and validate triggers, and offering coping mechanisms for sexual trauma; as well as for family, friends, and community allies wanting to provide support. 
jasmine johnson-decosta, the owner of blue pearl therapy llc, has been providing therapeutic services in a variety of settings for over 15 years. she has been fulfilled at helping clients work through challenging times and reach their goals. jasmine is a solution-focused therapist with an emphasis on a strength-based approach. her clients are able to identify their own strengths, resiliency, and resources to improve any situation causing distress. jasmine has extensive work with clients living with post traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), medical illness and injury counseling, military/civilian sexual trauma, veteran and caregiver related stressors. #metoo #jasminejohnson  @bluepearltherapyllc

text:
what does politics have to do with psychology? 
things that were once kept as private confusion have now risen to the surface through issues that are personal and impact us deeply. both at home in the workplace, these choices impact our families and their security. healthcare, non disclosure agreements, forced arbitration are all now common issues. 
changes on a macro level are hard to come by when repeated issues cannot be made public, â€œwill never be seen by a juryâ€ means that there is little incentive for change (just google google). it also adds to emotional labor on a daily basis.

text:
today, iâ€™m feeling grateful that at a young ageâ€”i was introduced to legally documenting every interaction that i had with my abuser. 
_____________________________________
iâ€™m grateful that at the age of 12â€”i would lock myself in a closet and pour through depositions and evidence exhibits that i stole in order to keep one step ahead of my abuser trying to steal me out of the country. he already told me that a judge would never believe meâ€”that i was crazyâ€”that i didnâ€™t have the â€œright perception of realityâ€ as i locked and barricaded my bedroom door one last time with him screaming. 
________________________________________________________
iâ€™m grateful that at the age of 13â€”i was forced to go to counseling with my abuser. it taught me that people would rather believe a respected male figureâ€”than believe the girl with fire in her eyes. ________________________________________________________
iâ€™m grateful to all the men who have beaten, grabbed, strangled, drugged, raped, or catcalledâ€”and then joked and called me a cunt for using my words to silence their abuse. it taught me that a good punch to the throat was always a solid move if you didnâ€™t want to hear their raw sewage of words pour out. 
_________________________________________________________
and i could keep going. we only really got up to the teen years.
___________________________________________________________
but what this really all meansâ€”is that in 3 daysâ€”iâ€™ll have a total of 24 years of experience in fucking shit up and taking names. 
___________________________________
and that feels really, damn good. 
hereâ€™s to the best birthday ever ğŸ’›

text:
via @wtopnews: there were 46 deaths from domestic violence in maryland between july 2017 and june 2018. the victims were remembered in a ceremony monday night, presided by maryland first lady yumi hogan. â€œas a mother and a grandmother, my heart breaks for the victims of these senseless tragedies,â€ hogan said.

the maryland network against domestic violence says 26 intimate partners were killed, including wives, girlfriends, husbands and boyfriends.

among the dead were five bystanders, including off-duty prince georgeâ€™s county police officer mujahid ramzziddin who was killed when he rushed to the aid of his brandywine, maryland neighbor.

fifteen abusive partners died, 10 of them were men in murder-suicides. â€œwhat we know is that it can and does happen in communities all across maryland regardless of socio-economic status, racial makeup and all other kinds of demographics,â€ said inga james, president of the maryland network against domestic violence.

text:
sometimes after a sexual assault or sexual abuse- your best option is to sue the perpetrator or the institution involved in the abuse for money to pay for your therapy or for money to show that they harmed you- to right a wrong. 
learn more about this process in the latest episode of slut or nut: the podcast, with personal injury and sexual assault/abuse lawyer simona jellinek.

most of these civil lawsuits result in a settlement for the survivor- which with the conviction rate in criminal trials being so low- sometimes a cash settlement can be more beneficial to the survivor than a two year jail sentence for the perpetrator or worse- no conviction at all. 
episode available on
 #soundcloud #itunes #youtube and #stitcher.

text:
so much and yet not enough of our focus is on self: self care, selfishness, self doubt, etc. what shouldnâ€™t get lost through it all, trend or not, is the fact that true change does originate within ourselves. for example, people cannot quit smoking â€œforâ€ another person but must want it themselves. similarly, changing negative thought patterns requires a deep and honest dialogue with yourself. if you canâ€™t admit what you may or may not be doing to impede changes, you canâ€™t truly say youâ€™ve tried everything you can to make improvements.
.
this has been a hard concept for me, not because i canâ€™t be honest with myself but because i realize i didnâ€™t ever dig deeply enough to challenge why or how i react a certain way.
.
as i learn more about the various emotions that feed into our actions, i see a bit more clearly that part of being honest with myself is acknowledging the feelings, however selfish or unreasonable they might seem to me, that may have driven me to react in a particular way.
.
i have always prided myself on my logical nature and it is an important portion of my ability to be honest and practical about my goals. however, emotions are not usually very logical. theyâ€™re the adjectives and filler that complete the story and fill in the blanks for our brains to make sense of the world around us.
.
reality and our perception of reality can easily get blended together into a confusing knot. being more in tune with myself is not intuitive for me and is going to continue to be something i have to integrate more completely into my life.
.
but the first step starts with me.
.
.
.
.
.

itâ€™s not an issue that makes the front pages. however, prison beatings â€” and murders â€” sexual assaults and bribery are not the only indignities to which prisoners are subjected. finding their voices in the era of #metoo, advocates say that women in jail, prison, holding facilities and even juvenile detention, depend on the whims of prison guards who might withhold sanitary items, giving them a few tissues instead â€” or nothing at all. often, the women are forced to buy such basic necessities in the prison store."

text: the unconscious survival mechanism of doubt. chapter 19 "we all know these people, and maybe we can recognize some of these traits in ourselves. the naysayers, the killjoys, the skeptics. the blamers, and complainers, the procrastinators and those who always have big plans that never come to fruition. because to have a negative view on life means that youâ€™ll never be unexpectedly disappointed. to expect failure means that youâ€™ll never feel broadsided, and to never finish anything means that you canâ€™t be criticizedâ€”because no one can criticize something that you didnâ€™t put out there for others to see. if we respond to any of lifeâ€™s uncertainties with doubt, we have the illusion of safety and control, even if it isnâ€™t conscious. the trap is that we end up criticizing ourselves, which fuels the doubt and fear we bring to lifeâ€™s uncertainties even moreâ€”and we get stuck in a trap that is damaging one person and one person only. ourselves." #healing #badass #trauma #community #yoga #meditation #women #metoo #mindfulness #men

spreading false information about an individual: up to 3 years in prison or up to rs. 1 million in fine or both.

whoever intentionally and publicly displays any information through an information system, which he knows to be false and intimidates or harms the reputation or privacy of an individual, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to three years or with fine which may extend to one million rupees or with both:

for example:

you know that a piece of information is wrong and you still post or share it on facebook about a person that damages his/her reputation

text:
the first time i heard the words â€œforgiveâ€ and â€œabuserâ€ used in the same sentence in a directive manner to me by my coach, i thought â€œno fucking way! no fucking way am i going to forgive the person who abused me. what he did was wrong. .
how could i forgive him for what he did?! i donâ€™t want to forgive him!â€
.
she interrupted the rant in my head suggesting that i not only forgive him but i also find the gift in the abuse. i broke my silence, â€œgift? what the hell kind of gift will i ever find in the abuse? there isnâ€™t a gift in that.â€
.
â€œjulie, hurt people hurt people. when people are hurt, they lash out and hurt other people â€“ sometimes consciously and other times they have no idea they are even doing it. since he was hurting you itâ€™s likely someone was hurting him, because what he did to you is not normal behavior. what he did to you comes from a hurt person.â€
.
up until that moment i never had the thought he had been abused or hurt by someone and therefore abused me. i finally understood the phrase hurt people, hurt people. however my new understanding didnâ€™t ease any of my pain or make me want to forgive him.
.
then she put a cherry on top sharing the quote: â€œholding onto anger is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to die.â€ (unknown)
.
what i learned after that is forgiveness is a process, and it was a process for me, not him. although it wasnâ€™t easy to forgive, over time i forgave him.
.
.
.
.

â€¦

// this really happened on february 13, 1542, in an age void of female rights and a #metoo revolution. this queen's story deserves to be heard... //
â€¢â€¢â€¢ today marks 477 years since katherine howard, the fifth and youngest queen of king henry viii, was sent to the block, by said king, to face her death. it's been a long time since then, but her memory still lives on in our hearts. if there's one thing everyone should know, it is that affair or no affair, whether guilty or victim, she did not deserve to die; she was just human like me and you. none of us is without fault. and none of us deserves to be sent to death by our spouse, especially not without a court hearing. may katherine be remembered for all her good qualities. <3 â€¢â€¢â€¢

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text: the talisman................................................ the onus of healing is shoved upon victims, survival a daily "why" left dangling as though unharmed people think the same. they don't. those who walk without the pain and the clatter of scars are so free it friggin sings. the view from the out-side a technicolor movie i saw as a kid...the vibrant motion overwhelming and foreign. my eyeballs shrieked with both fear and joy, the surprising exuberance coming into the brain as the very first taste of ice cream while skating on a half-frozen lake. "surely, i would be lost if i fell in?" the colorful landscape so different than my real life i absorbed it only to the surface, an over-full sponge of someone else's barf having only so much room. the other way life is the talisman, a lushly vibrant, living, breathing, singing movie watched from the middle of a crowded theater.

text: 5am thoughts....filling myself with hate was never an option. but holding onto the pain, on the other hand, was my weakness. internalizing what happened and feeling like i had to go through it alone turned into depression and thoughts of suicide that i have battled all of my life. in my later years, i am able to see things from a more mature perspective. i know that i canâ€™t hold onto things and that i need to just forgive, but when i say this, i do not mean forget. use the pain for inspiration, for art, for exercise, writing, for a template on how not to treat people. we learn from other peopleâ€™s mistakes just as often as we learn from our own. #selflove #abuseawareness #speakout #childabuseawareness #pray #metoo #overcome #strength #forgivenessisfreedom #soulsearching

text: "i think we should take into account, how people who have wished to seek justice, have been failed by the system. often naming and shaming is the last resort for people who have been failed by the justice system. that includes courts, systems within organizations, within schools etc. there is is a reason why so many stories of harassment have come out now; in this time, in this generation and that is: we finally have platforms like social media, with which we can reach a wider audience & be taken seriously. before these platforms, #namingandshaming did exist but within smaller circles so the ability to shut people out was very great & those stories never came out." writer and editor #hamnazubair pointed out the importance of #metoomovement in the session be khauf azad hai jeena mujhe: from #metoo to #neveragain #lahootimelo #anodetowomen #ibelieveher #lahooti #lahootimelo2019 #believesurvivors ğŸ“¸ @steermedia

text:
de liefde en ik
.
ik weet niet beter als dat ik mijn hele leven al aan het zoeken ben naar liefde, â€œde liefdeâ€. ik heb, opgroeiend in ons gezin, deze liefde gemist.
thuis had ik geen goed voorbeeld omdat mijn ouders vanaf dat ik geboren ben altijd ruzie maakten. zij hadden een haat/liefdes verhouding waardoor er weinig liefde aanwezig was. mijn moeder sprak vaak slecht over mijn vader, wat hij allemaal fout deed, wat ze niet van hem kreeg, bij hem miste en dat ze eigenlijk weg wilde bij hem.
.
mijn vader heb ik, daardoor een lange periode op afstand gehouden. ik gaf hem de schuld dat alles in ons gezin niet lekker liep. dat er zoveel ruzie was en wij ons ongelukkig voelden enz
tegen mijn moeder zei ik, na elke ruzie met mijn vader, wat zowat elke dag was, dat zij weg moest gaan bij hem. dan zei ze weer: ik wil niet dat mijn kinderen zonder vader opgroeien.
dat begreep ik dan niet, want nu hadden wij ook geen liefdevolle vader, geen liefdevol thuis. er was elke dag ruzie, strijd en ongemak.
.
mijn moeder had zichzelf al lang geleden verloren. bleef hangen in het patroon van ruzie maken zonder hierin verandering te brengen. om het heft in eigen handen te nemen en te kiezen voor geluk, haar geluk. in plaats daarvan schuilde ze achter haar â€œnegatieveâ€ overtuigingen, dat haar kinderen een vader moesten hebben in hun leven. nu begrijp ik dat mijn vader geen echte vader kon zijn door het toedoen van mijn moeder. dat heb ik heel lang niet kunnen zien.
.
wanneer je de les van de liefde nog niet geleerd hebt, kopieer je als het ware wat je hebt meegemaakt in jou huidige (liefdes)leven. je trekt een soortgelijke vrouw/man aan die dan een spiegelbeeld is van je vader/moeder.
je creÃ«ert een gezinssituatie / liefdesrelatie die in principe hetzelfde is als hoe het was in je opgroeiende jaren. je hebt het zo als voorbeeld gekregen van je ouders en dat is 'normaal ' voor jou, je weet (onbewust) niet beter.
.
.

text: like much of the pain felt in our lives, heartache comes from attachment and lack of surrender. we might not see it during the heartache, but people always come to our lives to teach us something and help us grow, and we must understand that once their mission in our lives is over, they move on and so do we.

text:
been watching @nbcsvu with @therealmariskahargitay , @kelligiddish , @icet , @peterscanavino etc. from the very first ep and was always a fan. 
but this last season got me thinking; in fact, i got thinking ever since the 2nd trans avery got murdered. and in season 20, #oliviabenson keeps sabotaging vics, even getting them murdered. good going, benson! but this is known, so i'm not getting into howÂ problematic benson is.

my main beef is that svu would not protect me. because i am fat. what? look at the vics! by far most are white, 99% are slim, and, other than the old ladies in the nursing home episode, pretty much 100% are what society considers attractive. fat, "ugly", old,Â or non-white vics clearly don't feel encouraged to report their rape in the svu universe - or they're just not worth raping to begin with? because clearly, hardly any people fitting that description are vics on that show. or is it that shit american tv doesÂ - insist that everyone be pretty?

either way, it makes not-so-pretty survivors like me feel abandoned by the ever so vocal message of the show. i imagine that vics of colour can relate. or vics with visible disabilities (who aren't redeemed by a pretty face), deformities, the elderly... i mean,Â even child vics are picked from pretty aisle, because even victims of child abuse gotta have an appearance that explains why the perp picked them, huh? pimple-covered, fat, four-eyed (native american/black/asian) kids don't get groomed oh wait they do, butÂ not on svu. i remember that being fat with shitty skin didn't save me, not at 7 and not at 27.

the fact that this show only depicts pretty and predominantly white and able-bodied, young-ish vics, and as such, only depicts pretty folks as worth protecting/as vulnerable, is utterly offensive and discouraging given #metoo & general gender- and sex-basedÂ violence & discrimination, because this show sure as hell discriminates â€“ hey, viewer's wouldn't want images of a screaming, naked fatty.

#lawandorder #lawandordersvu #nbcsvu #specialvictimsunit #mariskahargitay #kelligiddish #icet #sexualassault #waronwomen #rapeculture #survivors #fatphobia #womenofcolor #feminism #ineedfeminismbecause
